Tom, thanks.  Yes, that is another difficult one.  For some of us Vietnam was the most exciting thing to happen in our lives.  Some of us spend the rest of our lives trying to capture those feelings.<br><br>
Smelling the air after surviving a prolonged motar barrage. Seeing a sunrise after a scary night in a perimeter hole, seeing or imagining things in the night.  Walking around after a perimeter attack with the shakes and the taste of that cigarette.  The rush of adrenaline and the fear when confronted with the possiblility of not seeing the sun rise.  Aiming that rifle, squeezing the trigger and praying you got the enemy before they got you. And then knowing that you took a human life.  That's difficult.<br><br>
This is why a lot of firemen, police, and folks involved saving lives are vets.  Sure the discipline is one reason, but personally it is seeking that edge that was in Vietnam.  I don't know this is true of all these folks just the ones that were in my group.  These feelings were expressed.<br><br>
Putting all that into perspective is difficult.  Integrating that into your life today is even harder.  I've said this before. &quot;Changing your survival skills into coping skills.&quot;  Or another way is putting &quot;shades of grays&quot; into your life.  So everything isn't all black and white.<br><br>
So again guys, thanks for your support.  This is a thread that I've wanted to do for a while.<br><br>
Chet Botkins <br>
RVN 65-67<br>
1st. Cav 3/18th Arty<br>

